1
00:00:02,883 --> 00:00:10,731
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa.

2
00:00:11,292 --> 00:00:15,898
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:17,480 --> 00:00:23,827
So I thought tonight I'd tackle this problem of indulgence.

4
00:00:23,875 --> 00:00:30,681
So if I were to quote the Buddha, you see, the first discourse, which is really just a formalized teaching he had.

5
00:00:31,201 --> 00:00:34,344
I can't imagine that this is exactly what he said.

6
00:00:35,204 --> 00:00:44,874
But he says that indulgence in sensual pleasures, which is base, vulgar, worldly, ignoble and not beneficial.

7
00:00:45,853 --> 00:00:53,240
And then he says the practice of self-mortification, which is simply painful, ignoble and not beneficial.

8
00:00:53,878 --> 00:00:55,804
And then he talks about the middle path.

9
00:00:56,124 --> 00:01:01,777
So this middle path isn't a little bit of indulgence and a little bit of mortification.

10
00:01:01,817 --> 00:01:05,546
It's something which transcends them, right?

11
00:01:05,566 --> 00:01:07,652
That's the middle, as it were.

12
00:01:07,716 --> 00:01:15,549
It's a way of saying that there is a path which does not include either the indulgence or the practice of self-mortification.

13
00:01:16,049 --> 00:01:21,337
That self-mortification is blaming the body for our problems.

14
00:01:22,198 --> 00:01:29,370
So if your eye sees something which brings up lust, you start blaming the eye.

15
00:01:29,870 --> 00:01:32,474
Well, that wouldn't be correct, would it?

16
00:01:32,454 --> 00:01:43,617
So in those days, especially the James, they thought that the body itself was the product of our karma and you had to let go of the body.

17
00:01:43,938 --> 00:01:50,131
So to die, to stop eating was considered to be the way to go.

18
00:01:50,171 --> 00:01:53,737
And I believe elderly people do that even these days.

19
00:01:55,135 --> 00:01:57,558
Anyway, we're talking about indulgence.

20
00:01:58,079 --> 00:02:01,364
And this is an essay I've written really around eating.

21
00:02:01,965 --> 00:02:06,433
But hopefully I'll try and spread it out to include everything.

22
00:02:07,373 --> 00:02:08,975
So I always like the Greek myths.

23
00:02:09,576 --> 00:02:11,300
So how bad can greed get?

24
00:02:11,860 --> 00:02:18,070
So Aristothon, I'll say that again, Aristothon.

25
00:02:19,353 --> 00:02:21,055
I was practicing that as well, you see.

26
00:02:21,094 --> 00:02:23,538
It's a waste of time, me practicing these things.

27
00:02:23,519 --> 00:02:36,109
The Greek king of Thessaly had the temerity to build a banqueting hall over the shrine of Demeter, goddess of earth's fertility and protector of the harvest.

28
00:02:36,890 --> 00:02:40,278
She cursed him with insatiable hunger.

29
00:02:40,258 --> 00:02:44,788
First, he ate everything that was in his kingdom that was able to eat.

30
00:02:45,189 --> 00:02:49,018
And then he started on his people and even ate his own family.

31
00:02:49,919 --> 00:02:52,746
Finally, still famished, he ate himself.

32
00:02:53,366 --> 00:02:55,010
So that's how bad it can get.

33
00:02:56,240 --> 00:03:10,698
Actually, when I was staying at Kandaboda in Sri Lanka, there was an American turned up and he was telling me that when he got lost in the wilds once, he went through a period of a few days where he just didn't have any food.

34
00:03:11,498 --> 00:03:16,566
And when he eventually caught a pigeon, he said he just ripped it open and ate it raw.

35
00:03:17,187 --> 00:03:21,532
So I don't think we ever get as close to that sort of hunger usually.

36
00:03:22,293 --> 00:03:24,575
Normally, when we feel a bit peckish, we'll...

37
00:03:25,568 --> 00:03:27,471
we'll put an end to it as quick as we can.

38
00:03:29,112 --> 00:03:32,538
So, I mean, those are the extreme conditions, you see.

39
00:03:33,360 --> 00:03:38,026
But what we have to do, there are three things that we have to become clear about.

40
00:03:39,207 --> 00:03:41,671
Remember, this is the other side of suffering.

41
00:03:41,711 --> 00:03:45,056
So everybody, you know, like the depressions and the anxiety.

42
00:03:45,097 --> 00:03:46,960
So we know how to deal with that.

43
00:03:47,080 --> 00:03:53,550
But this indulgence is rather difficult because it's so close to enjoyment.

44
00:03:55,723 --> 00:04:01,479
So that's the first thing is to be able to distinguish when we're enjoying something as opposed to indulging it.

45
00:04:02,402 --> 00:04:10,746
And the second one is to begin to see the distinction between the body and the mind and what the body is actually giving us, which is pure.

46
00:04:10,725 --> 00:04:17,115
So all that's coming in, for instance, through the ears is the vibrations in the air.

47
00:04:17,737 --> 00:04:23,206
And then from there, it's taken into the mind and it's the mind which gives it meaning.

48
00:04:23,485 --> 00:04:28,074
So you get a bell, alarm bell, and so on and so forth.

49
00:04:28,855 --> 00:04:33,182
And then finally, to know the distinction between a desire and an action.

50
00:04:33,822 --> 00:04:38,370
So this is the Buddha making as clear as to what the role of the will is.

51
00:04:40,223 --> 00:04:40,684
Okay.

52
00:04:42,446 --> 00:04:48,233
So the first thing is to really begin to understand what the downside of indulgence is.

53
00:04:49,314 --> 00:04:59,528
The problem is that when we're indulging something, you know, we're getting like a food or we're out in nature and we're loving it and we're bathing in it.

54
00:05:01,170 --> 00:05:03,213
While we're doing that, there's not a problem.

55
00:05:03,293 --> 00:05:04,454
I mean, it's heaven, isn't it?

56
00:05:04,555 --> 00:05:06,416
We think it's Nibbana.

57
00:05:06,649 --> 00:05:11,997
it's the aftermath that we have to become sort of aware of.

58
00:05:12,358 --> 00:05:17,786
So the first thing that arises from that indulgence is of course that sort of compulsive behavior.

59
00:05:18,468 --> 00:05:24,576
So here, the psychology is the same as any addict.

60
00:05:25,418 --> 00:05:32,809
I mean, they've got it bad, but for most of us, it becomes a sort of obsessive thing that we need

61
00:05:34,543 --> 00:05:45,346
So, I mean, just to take a very simple example, I mean, everybody has a special time for a tea or coffee and biscuits, coffee and a piece of cake, you know.

62
00:05:45,935 --> 00:05:56,988
And when you get to that time, if you just sit in front of it, you'll feel the process of that wanting and the compulsive nature of having to have it.

63
00:05:57,170 --> 00:06:00,033
You can get quite depressed if you don't get it.

64
00:06:00,694 --> 00:06:01,935
But that's the other side too.

65
00:06:02,877 --> 00:06:12,870
So it's a case of recognizing that as soon as we have one of these unwholesome habits, there's a certain compulsion around that behavior.

66
00:06:16,951 --> 00:06:24,043
I've got an example here of somebody who gave up smoking and thought that they were completely over it.

67
00:06:24,725 --> 00:06:29,254
And then, you know, at a party, they just have that just one, just one cigarette.

68
00:06:29,735 --> 00:06:33,642
And before they're knowing it, of course, they're buying a packet.

69
00:06:33,663 --> 00:06:40,274
Now, I know that has a physical dependency to it, but it's the same sort of psychology even for biscuits.

70
00:06:42,432 --> 00:06:46,699
The second problem is the frustration that arises when we don't get what we want.

71
00:06:48,100 --> 00:06:50,824
So if you've forgotten to buy the tea, that's terrible.

72
00:06:51,567 --> 00:06:53,870
Or to buy the coffee, that's even worse sometimes.

73
00:06:55,372 --> 00:06:58,197
And Amazon, of course, has spent...

74
00:06:58,177 --> 00:07:15,954
Millions, millions on getting their products to the customer as quickly as possible, just knowing that if they can gratify a person's desire more quickly than anybody else, then they get their loyalty.

75
00:07:16,375 --> 00:07:17,737
And of course, it's worked.

76
00:07:19,473 --> 00:07:28,043
We get angry over silly things, you know, the bus doesn't arrive at the time and the train's late as usual and things like that.

77
00:07:28,564 --> 00:07:31,848
And that's the frustration of not getting what we want, you see.

78
00:07:31,968 --> 00:07:34,651
And that comes from an attachment to something.

79
00:07:36,593 --> 00:07:38,877
The third one is grief.

80
00:07:40,079 --> 00:07:48,348
So especially, well, with things, it's especially if you lose something which is treasured by you, you know,

81
00:07:49,206 --> 00:07:56,413
an engagement ring, a marriage ring, or some token of friendship, some heirloom, if that's stolen from you.

82
00:07:56,894 --> 00:08:10,406
I remember at college, my girlfriend at the time, she was living in this place with other girls and the landlord turned out to be some sort of thief.

83
00:08:10,608 --> 00:08:15,271
And just one day they found that all their little treasures were completely stolen.

84
00:08:15,331 --> 00:08:18,235
All the jewels that they had is absolutely awful.

85
00:08:20,947 --> 00:08:27,677
And of course, when we lose something like a mobile, I mean, we get more angry than anything, but there's a sense of grief there.

86
00:08:28,499 --> 00:08:39,214
And, you know, when it comes to objects, it's good to remind ourselves that the idea of possessing an object is a legal fiction.

87
00:08:39,634 --> 00:08:45,403
It's something that we presume on the object, that the object is mind.

88
00:08:46,244 --> 00:08:49,595
But actually, when you think about it, you can only use objects.

89
00:08:49,654 --> 00:08:51,120
You can only use your phone.

90
00:08:51,640 --> 00:08:53,447
And when the thief takes it, it's his.

91
00:08:53,506 --> 00:08:56,878
It's not mine anymore.

92
00:08:59,508 --> 00:09:01,870
So the fourth one is anxiety.

93
00:09:02,673 --> 00:09:10,102
So under anything we possess, I'm sure you will find some level of anxiety about loss.

94
00:09:10,864 --> 00:09:14,089
And the more we have, the more the anxiety is there.

95
00:09:14,950 --> 00:09:17,274
And you can see that from people who are very rich.

96
00:09:17,394 --> 00:09:20,538
Once they reach a billion, it's hardly enough.

97
00:09:20,577 --> 00:09:24,604
They've got to insure that billion by having another billion.

98
00:09:25,124 --> 00:09:30,434
And it's the same with other things that we have, like friendships.

99
00:09:30,495 --> 00:09:40,315
We feel more safe when we have lots of friendships, people whom we can call our friends, family, like that.

100
00:09:40,294 --> 00:09:42,317
And there's also to do with power.

101
00:09:42,479 --> 00:09:44,783
The more power you have, the more safe you feel.

102
00:09:45,163 --> 00:09:53,697
So when those things begin to dissipate, when they begin to lose them, that's when you touch this this underground anxiety we have.

103
00:09:53,717 --> 00:10:01,130
And of course, that anxiety goes right to the basis of the real of the the real problem that sits under everything.

104
00:10:01,491 --> 00:10:03,534
And that's the idea of a self self.

105
00:10:03,514 --> 00:10:10,764
And the self is telling us to enjoy ourselves, to try and make this life really enjoyable.

106
00:10:10,804 --> 00:10:18,416
And so when that joy begins to disappear that we become attached to, then you get that anxiety.

107
00:10:19,857 --> 00:10:24,625
Now, that isn't to say that there isn't enjoyment and the joys of life, right?

108
00:10:24,644 --> 00:10:26,147
And we'll come to that in a bit.

109
00:10:26,953 --> 00:10:33,147
So finally, and I don't think this is an exhaustive list, there's boredom.

110
00:10:33,287 --> 00:10:46,735
So if you remember, after the Buddha became fully liberated, Mara, the evil one, sent his three daughters and they were sensual pleasure, sexual pleasure and boredom.

111
00:10:47,068 --> 00:10:50,453
So this boredom is an aversive state.

112
00:10:51,014 --> 00:10:55,480
What used to give you happiness doesn't give you that happiness anymore.

113
00:10:55,861 --> 00:11:04,072
And if we look at it, it's actually not so much the happiness that we're after, it's that little sliver on top, which is the excitement.

114
00:11:04,854 --> 00:11:13,025
And that's the big delusion of our consumerist societies, to confuse happiness with excitement.

115
00:11:14,778 --> 00:11:20,706
So if you think of a Christmas cake, right, this is a British and Irish Christmas cake.

116
00:11:21,828 --> 00:11:25,073
You get the solid bit, the fruit cake underneath it all.

117
00:11:25,394 --> 00:11:30,022
And then you get this sliver at the top of marzipan and the icing, you see.

118
00:11:30,823 --> 00:11:34,929
And children will peel that off and just eat that, of course.

119
00:11:34,909 --> 00:11:39,759
And that, of course, gives the cake that little special zing, you see.

120
00:11:39,818 --> 00:11:45,809
So it's just an ordinary fruitcake unless you have that little bit of marzipan and icing on top.

121
00:11:46,671 --> 00:11:50,018
And of course, that's what gives you diabetes, isn't it?

122
00:11:50,238 --> 00:11:50,798
The sugar.

123
00:11:51,740 --> 00:11:52,923
But we're not worried about that.

124
00:11:53,102 --> 00:11:55,246
We'd rather just enjoy it.

125
00:11:55,226 --> 00:11:58,130
So it's the same with this happiness and excitement.

126
00:11:59,011 --> 00:12:20,778
And often when we give something up or when we do something, sorry, not give something up, when we actually make the right intention to just enjoy something and not to indulge, there's always that sense that we've lost a little bit of that little pleasure that we used to have through indulgence.

127
00:12:20,759 --> 00:12:23,148
And that's your renunciation.

128
00:12:23,568 --> 00:12:31,899
When the Buddha talks about renunciation, and that renunciation is the path to liberation, it's getting rid of that excitement.

129
00:12:32,317 --> 00:12:33,839
I mean, the Buddha was happy, you know.

130
00:12:34,100 --> 00:12:39,804
He actually says, when you get to Nibbana, you are contented and with it happy.

131
00:12:40,184 --> 00:12:48,613
So we're not going to lose contentment and happiness, but it's giving up that little sliver of excitement.

132
00:12:48,972 --> 00:12:52,775
Well, even though I say it's a little sliver for most, for a lot of people, that's what it is.

133
00:12:53,356 --> 00:13:02,325
And that's where you get this sort of clickbait that they talk about, you know, when people are scrolling through all these,

134
00:13:02,304 --> 00:13:08,340
fashions and computers and anything else that they want to feed off.

135
00:13:09,202 --> 00:13:15,658
And what it's doing is, at a physical level, we know it's sort of drenching the brain with dopamine.

136
00:13:15,678 --> 00:13:19,268
But at that mental level, it's that...

137
00:13:19,248 --> 00:13:20,770
what we call the attachment.

138
00:13:21,311 --> 00:13:22,533
That's the dependency.

139
00:13:23,114 --> 00:13:25,818
And that's what we mean when we talk about attachment.

140
00:13:25,859 --> 00:13:31,187
We mean that we are dependent on something to give us happiness.

141
00:13:31,268 --> 00:13:37,999
But when we look at that happiness, it's actually a little level of excited energy.

142
00:13:37,979 --> 00:13:45,095
And that's what we've got to give up because if we don't, it creates all these problems afterwards that we've been through.

143
00:13:45,154 --> 00:13:52,392
So we talked about compulsive behavior and frustration and grief and anxiety.

144
00:13:52,832 --> 00:13:55,919
And finally, this boredom and anxiety.

145
00:13:58,600 --> 00:14:12,428
If your whole life is about being excited and it begins to lose that excitement, it could be through illness, for instance, the boredom arises.

146
00:14:12,729 --> 00:14:17,138
And what boredom is saying is, what's the purpose of life if I can't be excited?

147
00:14:17,578 --> 00:14:19,342
I've got to search something.

148
00:14:19,322 --> 00:14:25,630
So you can see that this boredom is the sort of underlying engine of the whole consumerist society.

149
00:14:26,152 --> 00:14:30,597
It's the boredom that makes you seek the next thing that's going to make you excited.

150
00:14:31,339 --> 00:14:32,841
And we have this phrase, don't we?

151
00:14:32,941 --> 00:14:34,802
Variety is the spice of life.

152
00:14:35,504 --> 00:14:42,092
Well, that sort of attitude is the path to perdition, the path to hell.

153
00:14:43,975 --> 00:14:45,157
But that's not necessary.

154
00:14:45,356 --> 00:14:46,578
We can just be happy.

155
00:14:50,355 --> 00:15:04,686
So, the big thing that we have to do is to make sure that whenever we're going to do something which is going to bring happiness, is to be very clear about our intention.

156
00:15:04,750 --> 00:15:05,029
Right.

157
00:15:05,350 --> 00:15:10,578
So just taking food as a as an example, which is pretty straightforward.

158
00:15:11,581 --> 00:15:12,903
What's the purpose of eating?

159
00:15:12,942 --> 00:15:15,888
You know, the real purpose of eating is to nourish the body.

160
00:15:16,128 --> 00:15:21,797
That's the that's the real so that we can continue living and practicing and doing our practice.

161
00:15:22,485 --> 00:15:26,850
The fact that it tastes nice is part and parcel of that process.

162
00:15:26,951 --> 00:15:35,120
It might not be the taste that we expected, et cetera, et cetera, but at least that's just there, but we're not eating it for that reason.

163
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:41,025
So we go back to that little phrase, are we eating to live or living to eat, right?

164
00:15:41,787 --> 00:15:48,274
And it's just making those intentions very clear to ourselves and moving from that intention.

165
00:15:48,254 --> 00:15:51,837
And that's what undermines this desire for excitement.

166
00:15:56,683 --> 00:16:01,971
And it's very difficult to separate excitement from indulgence.

167
00:16:01,990 --> 00:16:04,573
You see, aversion is clear.

168
00:16:05,434 --> 00:16:09,519
Aversion pushes you away from the object you don't want to know.

169
00:16:09,719 --> 00:16:18,631
To be aware of aversion is much easier because it separates out from what it's averse to, same with fear.

170
00:16:19,506 --> 00:16:22,091
But when it comes to indulgence, it sort of melds.

171
00:16:22,171 --> 00:16:25,736
It's all little, you know, the connection is melding.

172
00:16:25,777 --> 00:16:31,265
So it's very difficult to sort of pull it apart and to see what the indulgence actually is.

173
00:16:31,966 --> 00:16:42,543
And of course, one way to do that is if we find ourselves having a habit which is compulsive is, of course, is to stop it.

174
00:16:43,384 --> 00:16:48,409
And when the desire comes, you sort of sit with the agony of letting go of that.

175
00:16:49,289 --> 00:17:00,399
One example I used to use, it doesn't work anymore, as you'll see, was to have a favorite TV program, you know, a serial or something like that.

176
00:17:01,260 --> 00:17:05,404
And you sort of turn it on and just look at the blank screen.

177
00:17:05,924 --> 00:17:07,707
And that would send you absolutely berserk.

178
00:17:07,826 --> 00:17:13,392
These days, of course, you can't do that because everybody's got iPlayer or something else.

179
00:17:13,372 --> 00:17:21,882
But the whole point of renunciation or an act of renunciation is to contact that desire.

180
00:17:23,063 --> 00:17:27,968
It's an unwholesome desire, the unwholesome desire.

181
00:17:28,709 --> 00:17:34,516
And as you work with that over time, of course, that habit begins to dissolve.

182
00:17:34,576 --> 00:17:41,083
It's not being fed and therefore it just begins to die away.

183
00:17:41,063 --> 00:17:53,582
And then once it's got low again, once you've got it down to a decent basis of control, then, of course, you simply have to watch that it doesn't get the better of you again.

184
00:17:53,882 --> 00:17:54,363
That's all.

185
00:17:55,003 --> 00:17:57,827
But eventually, we've got to give all that up, you see.

186
00:17:57,847 --> 00:18:01,653
And we don't give it up unless we see...

187
00:18:01,786 --> 00:18:06,355
the juice that comes from it, the fruit of that renunciation.

188
00:18:07,016 --> 00:18:20,502
And so if you take something which you can see is compulsive, it might be just a cup of tea at a certain time of day, and you just sit there with the empty cup, right?

189
00:18:21,226 --> 00:18:23,669
And you get that feeling of wanting to want it.

190
00:18:23,689 --> 00:18:26,873
And if you just sit with it, it's quite remarkable.

191
00:18:26,913 --> 00:18:34,241
If you just sit with it and wait for that desire to go away, that bad energy, remember, is transformed.

192
00:18:34,823 --> 00:18:39,669
And what you find is that suddenly you're contented and you don't want a cup of tea.

193
00:18:41,570 --> 00:18:45,816
And that's the joy of renunciation.

194
00:18:45,981 --> 00:18:50,646
So remember, we're not trying to confuse enjoyment with indulgence.

195
00:18:51,607 --> 00:18:56,934
And it all comes down really to our intentions.

196
00:18:57,434 --> 00:19:08,768
So the more we're aware of our intentions and we correct our intentions towards just enjoying something, then you'll find yourself being a bit more contented with the way things are.

197
00:19:09,469 --> 00:19:11,090
And with it, happiness, right?

198
00:19:11,111 --> 00:19:11,971
With it, happiness.

199
00:19:14,450 --> 00:19:26,990
So, yeah, just to end off with the Buddha's own quote, you know, he talks about...

200
00:19:27,663 --> 00:19:30,425
The taste of nirvana is freedom, right?

201
00:19:30,465 --> 00:19:34,329
The taste of the sea, the taste of the ocean is salt.

202
00:19:34,349 --> 00:19:38,354
And just as that has a taste, the taste of nirvana is freedom.

203
00:19:38,433 --> 00:19:39,795
Freedom from what?

204
00:19:39,815 --> 00:19:42,857
Freedom from this sort of compulsive desire, yeah?

205
00:19:43,479 --> 00:19:48,344
And I mean, remember, this is the desiring side for pleasure, right?

206
00:19:48,384 --> 00:19:51,988
Remember, there's the other side too, which is all about suffering.

207
00:19:52,028 --> 00:19:56,471
It's all about anxiety, depression, et cetera, et cetera.

